<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-01-04T17:14:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-01-04T17:14:00-05:00" n="904" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d904">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 422.11G93/896</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Quito</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-01-04T17:00:00-05:14">
                                    <hi rend="italic">January 4, 1917, 5 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>My telegram of January 3, 1 p.m. The Minister for Foreign Affairs this
                            afternoon requested extension of time till next Tuesday to answer my
                            inquiry as to when Ecuador will resume deposits. I granted extension but
                            informed him that owing to the great interest of my Government in the
                            subject I would immediately telegraph the Department of the
                            extension.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hartman</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>